defining-lists_key2: Lists ko define kar ne ke liye hum `square brackets use karte hai` - [].
defining-lists_key3: Jab bhi aap `[` dekhein, toh samjhe, list ki definition shuru ho gayi hai, aur `]` se list ki defintion khatam ho gayi hai.
defining-lists_key5: Iss example mein hum kuch bachon ki naam ki list store kar rahe hain.
defining-lists_key6: Aakhri line mein humne `type` ka use kiya hai. `type` function se hum dekhenge `python` mein iska type kya hai.
defining-lists_key7: Yeh ek `strings ki list` hai kyunki iski saari values mein `string` hain.
defining-lists_key8: **Note kariye, ki LIST ko start karne ke liye `[` use hota hai and band karne ke liye `]` use hota hai. `[ ]` ki shape square jaise dekhti hai, isliye inhe SQUARE BRACKEtS kaha jata hai**
defining-lists_key9: Lists ke andar hum koi bhi object daal sakte hain. Yeh `string`, `integer` ya kisi bhi aur data type ka ho sakta hai.
defining-lists_key11: Yeh kuch banks ke naam ki list hai
defining-lists_key13: Yeh ek student ke boards ki marks ki list hai.
defining-lists_key15: Yeh pichle saat dinon mein temperatures ki list hai.
defining-lists_key16: Lekin hum jab bhi ek list `variable` pe `type` function ka use karenge, toh humesha uska type list dikhayega. Lekin list ke andar kuch bhi type ho sakte hain.
defining-lists_key18: Aap apne friends ki ek `list` banaye
defining-lists_key19: Aap aap jin jin countries ko visit karna chahte hai unki ek `list` banaye
defining-lists_key20: Aap peechle 5 mahine ke `total expenses` kitne hue, uski ek `list` banaye (jaise maan lo, peechle mahine 58750 ke expenses hue, and so on)
